description: From Middle English superfluous, from Latin superfluus (“superfluous”), from superfluō (“overflow”), from super (“above, more than, over”) + fluō (“flow”). Compare mellifluous and fluid, also from Latin. Literally corresponds to overflow, which is from Germanic, rather than Latin.

adjectives.description: superfluous (comparative more superfluous, superlative most superfluous)

entries.meaning: In excess of what is required or sufficient.
examples: With a full rain suit, carrying an umbrella may be superfluous.
